    "output": "To extract subtitles from a video file and convert them into speech audio using text-to-speech (TTS), ffmpeg alone cannot perform TTS conversion because it does not have built-in text-to-speech capabilities. Instead, the process involves two main steps:\n\n1. Extract subtitles from the video as a plain text file.\n2. Use an external TTS engine or service to convert the subtitle text to an audio file (MP3).\n\nHere is a detailed approach assuming open-source tools:\n\n### Step 1: Extract subtitles from video.mkv to srt file (if not already separate)\nIf the subtitles are embedded in video.mkv:\n\n```bash\nffmpeg -i video.mkv -map 0:s:0 srt.srt\n```\n\nThis extracts the first subtitle stream as srt.srt.\n\n### Step 2: Use a TTS tool (e.g., `espeak`, `gtts-cli`, or any other TTS engine) to convert srt.srt to audio\n\nFor example, using `gtts-cli` (Google Text-to-Speech Python CLI), assuming you have Python and gtts installed:\n\n```bash\ngtts-cli -f srt.srt -o tts.mp3\n```\n\nAlternatively, with `espeak` you could:\n\n```bash\nespeak -f srt.srt --stdout | ffmpeg -i pipe: -codec:a libmp3lame -qscale:a 2 tts.mp3\n```\n\n### Summary\n\n- ffmpeg handles subtitle extraction.\n- External TTS tools convert text into audio.\n- You then encode the generated audio into MP3.\n\nIf you want a pure ffmpeg command just for subtitle extraction, here is that:\n\n```bash\nffmpeg -i video.mkv -map 0:s:0 srt.srt\n```\n\nSince TTS is beyond ffmpegâ€™s scope, choose your preferred TTS solution next.\n\n---\n\nIf you want me to help with a specific TTS engine, please specify it so I can provide the command.",
